<subSubSection id="0F8705EBFFB4FF9B10B59CDBFC6BFB79" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="61" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="47225660FFB4FF9810B59CDBFBA6FE13" blockId="5.[151,1437,152,418]" box="[198,1146,391,418]" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB4FF9810B59CDBFE8FFE10" bold="true" box="[198,339,391,417]" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is derived from the African ethnic group “ 
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB4FF98146E9CD4FBB7FE13" box="[1053,1131,392,418]" class="Insecta" family="Nogodinidae" genus="Fovealvus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nama">Nama</taxonomicName>
”.
</paragraph>
<caption id="13E206E8FFB4FF9810E49A01FEB6F86D" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/176308/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" targetBox="[284,1312,420,1885]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph id="47225660FFB4FF9810E49A01FEB6F86D" blockId="5.[151,1436,1885,2012]" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB4FF9810E49A01FE83F8C4" bold="true" box="[151,351,1885,1909]" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">FIGURES 17–23.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB4FF9811159A02FDCBF8C4" box="[358,535,1886,1909]" class="Insecta" family="Nogodinidae" genus="Fovealvus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nama">
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB4FF9811159A02FDCBF8C4" box="[358,535,1886,1909]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="60">Fovealvus nama</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
gen. et sp. nov., female genitalia. 17, posterior connective lamina of gonapophyses IX and gonospiculum bridge, dorsal view; 18, same, lateral view; 19, anal tube, dorsal view; 20, anal tube, lateral view; 21, anterior connective lamina of gonapophyse VIII and gonocoxa VIII, lateral view; 22, 23, fragment of bursa copulatrix microsculpture.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="47225660FFB7FF9B10E49DC4FEC4FF03" blockId="6.[151,280,152,178]" box="[151,280,152,178]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph id="47225660FFB7FF9B10E49DB4FC6BFB79" blockId="6.[151,1437,232,1224]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">
In the modern 
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B11369DB4FE1DFEB3" box="[325,449,232,258]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Hemiptera</taxonomicName>
literature there are two terms used for special receptive hairs of the body – “trichobothria” and “sensory pit”. The first one is more commonly used by heteropterists, but the second one by specialists of Auchenorrhyncha. The term trichobothria was proposed by Dahl for “a very long slender seta, set in a cup-like depression in the cuticle or on a small dome”; “the trichobothria is usually longer than the surrounding setae and oriented at more or less right angle to the cuticle, whereas most setae form an acute angle with the surrounding body surface” (
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B123D9CECFD3EFE7B" author="Schuh" box="[590,738,432,458]" pageId="6" pageNumber="62" refString="Schuh, R. T. (1975) The structure, distribution, and taxonomic importance of trichobothria in the Miridae (Hemiptera). American Museum Novitates, 2585, 1 - 26." type="journal article" year="1975">
Schuh 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B12D09CECFD3EFE7B" box="[675,738,432,458]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="1975.0">1975</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). A sensory pit is defined as “a small hole with horizontal seta directed inwards and diverging from its border; the length of the seta is not greater than diameter of the hole” (
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B10959F5CFE71FDAB" author="Emeljanov" box="[230,429,512,538]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" refString="Emeljanov, A. F. (2001) Larval characters and their ontogenetic development in Fulgoroidea (Homoptera, Cicadina). Zoosystematica Rossica, 9 (1) (2000), 101 - 121." type="journal article" year="2001">
Emeljanov 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B111D9F5CFE71FDAB" box="[366,429,512,538]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Trichobothria are commonly found in the adults of Heteroptera, but sensory pits are probably absent in the group. In Auchenorrhyncha sensory pits are specific organs in fulgoroid larvae and are very rare in adults (
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B110C9F0CFD94FDDB" author="Emeljanov" box="[383,584,592,618]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" refString="Emeljanov, A. F. (2001) Larval characters and their ontogenetic development in Fulgoroidea (Homoptera, Cicadina). Zoosystematica Rossica, 9 (1) (2000), 101 - 121." type="journal article" year="2001">
Emeljanov 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B127A9F0CFD94FDDB" box="[521,584,592,618]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
); but trichobothria also present in both. 
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B14579F0CFB41FDD8" box="[1060,1181,592,617]" class="Insecta" family="Nogodinidae" genus="Fovealvus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB7FF9B14579F0CFB41FDD8" box="[1060,1181,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Fovealvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="6EDA3709FFB7FF9B14D69F0CFACDFDDB" box="[1189,1297,592,618]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B153F9F0CFE1FFD23" authority="Waterhouse, 1839" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1839" class="Insecta" family="Tropiduchidae" genus="Alleloplasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB7FF9B153F9F0CFF07FD20" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Alleloplasis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B109A9F24FE1FFD23" author="Waterhouse" box="[233,451,632,658]" pageId="6" pageNumber="62" refString="Waterhouse, G. R. (1839) Descriptions of some new species of exotic insects. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, 2, 188 - 196." type="journal article" year="1839">
Waterhouse, 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B11FB9F24FE1FFD23" box="[392,451,632,658]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="1839.0">1839</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B11AB9F24FC79FD23" authority="Gnezdilov 2007" authorityName="Gnezdilov" authorityYear="2007" box="[472,933,632,658]" class="Insecta" family="Tropiduchidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Tropiduchidae sensu 
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B12929F24FC79FD23" author="Gnezdilov" box="[737,933,632,658]" pageId="6" pageNumber="62" refString="Gnezdilov, V. M. (2007) On the systematic positions of the Bladinini Kirkaldy, Tonginae Kirkaldy, and Trienopinae Fennah (Homoptera, Fulgoroidea). Zoosystematica Rossica 15 (2), (2006), 293 - 297." type="journal article" year="2007">
Gnezdilov 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B131A9F24FC79FD23" box="[873,933,632,658]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="2007.0">2007</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
) have trichobothria and sensory pits on abdominal sternites (figs 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B11B29FFCFDDCFD0B" box="[449,512,672,698]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="7.0" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="4.0">4–10</number>
). Both structures probably are used as mechanoreceptors or receptors of atmospheric humidity (
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B111E9F94FE23FD53" author="Schuh" box="[365,511,712,738]" pageId="6" pageNumber="62" refString="Schuh, R. T. (1975) The structure, distribution, and taxonomic importance of trichobothria in the Miridae (Hemiptera). American Museum Novitates, 2585, 1 - 26." type="journal article" year="1975">
Schuh 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B11B29F94FE23FD53" box="[449,511,712,738]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="1975.0">1975</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B12789F94FCD0FD53" author="Holzinger" box="[523,780,712,738]" pageId="6" pageNumber="62" refString="Holzinger, W. E., Emeljanov, A. F. &amp; Kammerlander, I. (2002) The family Cixiidae Spinola, 1839 (Hemiptera: Fulgoromorpha) - a review. Denisia 0 4, zugleich Katalogue des OO. Landesmuseums, N. F. 176, 113 - 138." type="book chapter" year="2002">
Holzinger 
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB7FF9B12FA9F94FD18FD50" box="[649,708,712,737]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">et al.</emphasis>
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B12BF9F94FCD0FD53" box="[716,780,712,738]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B13539F94FC61FD53" author="Sweet" box="[800,957,712,738]" pageId="6" pageNumber="62" refString="Sweet, M. H. (1996) Comparative external morphology of the pregenital abdomen in Hemiptera. In: Schaefer, C. W. (ed.), Studies on Hemipteran phylogeny. Lanham, Maryland: Thomas Say publications in entomology: proceedings. Entomological Society of America, pp. 119 - 158." type="book chapter" year="1996">
Sweet (
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B130B9F94FC69FD53" box="[888,949,712,738]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="1996.0">1996</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
suggested that presence of trichobothria is an autapomorphy of Fulgoromorpha+Coleorrhyncha+Heteroptera. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B14159FACFAE6FCBB" author="Emeljanov" box="[1126,1338,752,778]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" refString="Emeljanov, A. F. (2001) Larval characters and their ontogenetic development in Fulgoroidea (Homoptera, Cicadina). Zoosystematica Rossica, 9 (1) (2000), 101 - 121." type="journal article" year="2001">
Emeljanov (
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B14869FACFAEEFCBB" box="[1269,1330,752,778]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="2001.0">2001</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
sensory pits are strictly of tergal nature. Until now in the Fulgoromorpha sensory pits on abdominal sternites were known only in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B11CC9E1CFD96FCE8" box="[447,586,832,857]" class="Insecta" family="Tropiduchidae" genus="Alleloplasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB7FF9B11CC9E1CFD96FCE8" box="[447,586,832,857]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Alleloplasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Two described species of the genus – 
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B14679E1CFAB7FCEB" authority="Waterhouse, 1839" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1839" box="[1044,1387,832,858]" class="Insecta" family="Tropiduchidae" genus="Alleloplasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="darwini">
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB7FF9B14679E1CFB4CFCE8" box="[1044,1168,832,857]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">A. darwini</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B14E49E1CFAB7FCEB" author="Waterhouse" box="[1175,1387,832,858]" pageId="6" pageNumber="62" refString="Waterhouse, G. R. (1839) Descriptions of some new species of exotic insects. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, 2, 188 - 196." type="journal article" year="1839">
Waterhouse, 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B15439E1CFAB7FCEB" box="[1328,1387,832,858]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="1839.0">1839</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B10E49E34FE60FC33" authority="Fennah, 1949" authorityName="Fennah" authorityYear="1949" box="[151,444,872,898]" class="Insecta" family="Tropiduchidae" genus="Alleloplasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespula">
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB7FF9B10E49E34FECEFC30" box="[151,274,872,897]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">A. vespula</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B11689E34FE60FC33" author="Fennah" box="[283,444,872,898]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" refString="Fennah, R. G. (1949) New exotic Fulgoroidea. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, 20 (12), 585 - 606." type="journal article" year="1949">
Fennah, 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B11F29E34FE60FC33" box="[385,444,872,898]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="1949.0">1949</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
differ from each other in number of pits (
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B13DD9E34FB91FC33" author="Fennah" box="[942,1101,872,898]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" refString="Fennah, R. G. (1949) New exotic Fulgoroidea. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, 20 (12), 585 - 606." type="journal article" year="1949">
Fennah 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B147D9E34FB91FC33" box="[1038,1101,872,898]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="1949.0">1949</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B14F09E34FB20FC30" box="[1155,1276,872,897]" class="Insecta" family="Nogodinidae" genus="Fovealvus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB7FF9B14F09E34FB20FC30" box="[1155,1276,872,897]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Fovealvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="6EDA3709FFB7FF9B15779E34FAACFC33" box="[1284,1392,872,898]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
the male and female have 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B11EF9ECEFE77FC1D" box="[412,427,914,940]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="6.0">6</number>
pairs of sensory pits on hind margin of 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B130B9ECEFC5AFC1D" box="[888,902,914,940]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="6.0">6</number>
th abdominal sternite (figs 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B14C69ECEFB3DFC1D" box="[1205,1249,914,940]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="4.5">4, 5</number>
) and the female also has a couple of pits at the middle of 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B12069EE1FD58FC66" box="[629,644,957,983]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="7.0">7</number>
th sternite (figs 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B13419EE1FCBCFC66" box="[818,864,957,983]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="6.7">6, 7</number>
). Apparently the presence of pits on the abdominal sternites in these two genera is only analogous, because the genera 
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B139B9EBAFBAFFC4E" box="[1000,1139,998,1023]" class="Insecta" family="Tropiduchidae" genus="Alleloplasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB7FF9B139B9EBAFBAFFC4E" box="[1000,1139,998,1023]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Alleloplasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B14DC9EBAFAF4FC4E" box="[1199,1320,998,1023]" class="Insecta" family="Nogodinidae" genus="Fovealvus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB7FF9B14DC9EBAFAF4FC4E" box="[1199,1320,998,1023]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Fovealvus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="6EDA3709FFB7FF9B15439EB9FA40FC4E" box="[1328,1436,997,1023]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
clearly differ in the structure of the male and female genitalia and belong to different families (
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B15539951FF0BFBFE" author="Gnezdilov" pageId="6" pageNumber="62" refString="Gnezdilov, V. M. (2007) On the systematic positions of the Bladinini Kirkaldy, Tonginae Kirkaldy, and Trienopinae Fennah (Homoptera, Fulgoroidea). Zoosystematica Rossica 15 (2), (2006), 293 - 297." type="journal article" year="2007">
Gnezdilov 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B10E49969FF0BFBFE" box="[151,215,1077,1103]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="2007.0">2007</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Similar analogous sensory organs are known also for 
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B132C9969FC1EFBFE" box="[863,962,1077,1103]" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cixiidae</taxonomicName>
(the tribe Bennini Metcalf, for instance, 
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B10E49902FDF9FBC9" authority="Walker, 1857" authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1857" box="[151,549,1118,1144]" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" genus="Bennaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="praestans">
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB7FF9B10E49902FEA2FBC6" box="[151,382,1118,1143]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Bennaria praestans</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B11F59902FDF9FBC9" author="Walker" box="[390,549,1118,1144]" pageId="6" pageNumber="62" refString="Walker, F. (1857) Catalogue of the Homopterous insects collected at Sarawak, Borneo, by Mr. A. R. Wallace, with descriptions of new species. Journal of the Proceedings of the Linnean Society. London, 1, 141 - 175." type="journal article" year="1857">
Walker, 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B119A9902FDF9FBC9" box="[489,549,1118,1144]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="1857.0">1857</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B124E9902FCE2FBC9" author="Holzinger" box="[573,830,1118,1144]" pageId="6" pageNumber="62" refString="Holzinger, W. E., Emeljanov, A. F. &amp; Kammerlander, I. (2002) The family Cixiidae Spinola, 1839 (Hemiptera: Fulgoromorpha) - a review. Denisia 0 4, zugleich Katalogue des OO. Landesmuseums, N. F. 176, 113 - 138." type="book chapter" year="2002">
Holzinger 
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB7FF9B12CF9902FD25FBC6" box="[700,761,1118,1143]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">et al.</emphasis>
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B13739902FCE2FBC9" box="[768,830,1118,1144]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B13089902FC45FBC9" box="[891,921,1118,1144]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="10.0">10</number>
e) and the tribe Bennarellini Emeljanov, for instance, 
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B117699DAFC5CFB11" authority="Holzinger &amp; Kunz, 2006" authorityName="Holzinger &amp; Kunz" authorityYear="2006" box="[261,896,1158,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" genus="Noabennarella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costaricensis">
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB7FF9B117699DAFD89FB2E" box="[261,597,1158,1183]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Noabennarella costaricensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B122F99DAFC5CFB11" author="Holzinger" box="[604,896,1158,1184]" pageId="6" pageNumber="62" refString="Holzinger, W. E. &amp; Kunz, G. (2006) A new genus and species of Bennarellini from Costa Rica (Hemiptera: Fulgoromorpha: Cixiidae). Zootaxa, 1353, 53 - 61." type="journal article" year="2006">
Holzinger &amp; Kunz, 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B133699DAFC5CFB11" box="[837,896,1158,1184]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="2006.0">2006</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B13FD99DAFAD6FB11" author="Holzinger" box="[910,1290,1158,1184]" pageId="6" pageNumber="62" refString="Holzinger, W. E. &amp; Kunz, G. (2006) A new genus and species of Bennarellini from Costa Rica (Hemiptera: Fulgoromorpha: Cixiidae). Zootaxa, 1353, 53 - 61." type="journal article" year="2006">
Holzinger &amp; Kunz 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B140299DAFB73FB11" box="[1137,1199,1158,1184]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="2006.0">2006</number>
, fig. 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B149999DAFAD6FB11" box="[1258,1290,1158,1184]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="12.0">12</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), and 
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B152299DAFF3BFB79" class="Insecta" family="Achilixiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Achilixiidae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B108B99F2FEB1FB76" box="[248,365,1198,1223]" class="Insecta" family="Achilixiidae" genus="Achilixius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB7FF9B108B99F2FEB1FB76" box="[248,365,1198,1223]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Achilixius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. and 
<taxonomicName id="809D2DE3FFB7FF9B11AE99F2FD8DFB76" box="[477,593,1198,1223]" class="Insecta" family="Achilixiidae" genus="Bebaiotes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="75E98A72FFB7FF9B11AE99F2FD8DFB76" box="[477,593,1198,1223]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="61">Bebaiotes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp.) (
<bibRefCitation id="230C2B91FFB7FF9B12D299F2FC76FB79" author="Wilson" box="[673,938,1198,1224]" pageId="6" pageNumber="62" refString="Wilson, M. R. (1989) The planthopper family Achilixiidae (Homoptera, Fulgoroidea): a synopsis with a revision of the genus Achilixius. Systematic Entomology, 14, 487 - 506." type="journal article" year="1989">
Wilson 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B128D99F2FCE7FB79" box="[766,827,1198,1224]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="1989.0">1989</number>
, figs 
<number id="F1554447FFB7FF9B130999F2FC76FB79" box="[890,938,1198,1224]" pageId="6" pageNumber="61" value="5.0" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.0">4–6</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
